Terry McClure Story
After a very vigorous life plowing whole fields with his grandpa’s tractor by the age of 8, playing football in high school and following his heart into his lifelong career in law enforcement, in January 2012 Terry began experiencing difficulty with mobility such as stumbling and falling and also being unable to lift and hold onto things. These symptoms slowly progressed to a very pronounced weakness in his arms to the point that he couldn’t lift his keys to unlock a lock or even lift a cup for a drink. A series of events and doctors’ visits finally led to the Kansas University Medical Center on January 24, 2013 and the diagnosis of ALS. 
Terry was told to immediately quit his job as head of the Cowley County Jail in Winfield, Kansas, abruptly ending his career in law enforcement. This has also altered Terry’s ability to participate in activities supporting his love of firearms which includes over 20 years teaching classes in firearm safety and how to shoot plus spending countless hours over the years encouraging people to further their marksmanship skills. 
Terry and Becca have been married nearly 8 years and have made a very loving family with Becca’s 3 kids, Damyan (18, U.S. Navy), Brenna (15) and Aley (13). Through being foster parents they met and, on July 3, 2012, adopted 4 wonderful kids from the same family: Dylan (7), Chloe (6), Lola (4) and Max (2). Wow! Six kids at home and now Terry will never work again! 
Terry has dedicated his life to helping others and is a friend of mine and many others. Its time we give back to him and hey..you may just win something for your kindness.

The P30 was made from 1990 - 1994 by Grendel Inc. of Rockledge, Florida. They eventually faded away (largely due to the first assault weapon ban), but were later reborn as Kel Tec. The P30 is the father of Kel Tec's popular and hard to find PMR 30 which is also a full size 30 shot semi-auto pistol in .22 Mag caliber. title: For Sale/Trade:  Stoeger Cougar 8000 F
location: East Hill Neighborhood, Eau Claire, Wisconsin
postcontent:
This Stoeger Cougar 8000 F model is a 9mm Full-size (15+1) pistol that is in great shape. It is 2 year old, and I have only put about 100-200 rounds through it, and cleaned it after every range trip. This is basically a Beretta, but instead of it being made in Italy, it is made in Turkey so the gun is overall is a little less expensive. This gun is great for lefties, too, due to ambidextrous thumb safety. Great for home defense or just 'plinking'. New these are around $400 or $450 + tax.
This comes with the firearm, a hard case, the manual, and 4 - 15 round magazines (originally came with only 2). For the right price I will also add 100 rounds of 9mm (VERY hard to find right now.) [please note: not looking to sell the ammo/mags separately as of yet, don't bother to ask]

In the interest of full disclosure: This gun does occasionally jam (stovepipe)[for those that don't know what that means, this is a malfunction where sometimes after the gun fires, instead of properly ejecting the SPENT cartridge, the spent (now empty) cartridge gets trapped when the slide is coming forward, thus jamming the gun]. I have done research and found other users who have experienced this same type of jam repeatedly, and the solving of this problem seems to be 'breaking the gun in' meaning firing a couple of hundred rounds through it to loosen up the recoil spring enough to prevent it snapping back too quickly and catching the spent shell. Another thing other users have reportedly done is used +P rounds to loosen it up. As there is a shortage of 9mm lately I haven't tried this. But someone else should be able to use this as a 'project gun' and get it working fine, everything else is great besides this issue. I haven't tried replacing the recoil spring either.

Selling this gun AS IS.

Feel free to email me with questions or if you want some pictures/further details.
